                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                <placeName>New Orleans</placeName>\n                <date>5th July 5626</date>\n            </p>\n            <p>\n                <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>\n            </p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">\n                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>\n            </p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(2)\">Dear Sir,</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(3)\">Your letter on your return home duly reached<lb/> me. I regret very\n                sincerely to learn of your impaired health, of which<lb/> my\n                    <placeName>Richmond</placeName> correspondents had before informed me; but most\n                earnest-<lb/>ly do I pray that further tidings may be of a happier character.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">The lukewarmness and indifference that<lb/> you noticed in your\n                recent Southern trip, in religious matters, had<lb/> long ago been perceptible to\n                me, and occasioned serious and painful<lb/> thought. This degeneracy has been\n                creeping along for some time and<lb/> I see fearful signs of its continuous\n                progress. The battle between<lb/> Principle and Gain almost invariably terminates in\n                favor of the<lb/> latter; hence those leaders who will smooth away the\n                “difficulties”<lb/> which beset the path of conformity with recognized duties,\n                and<lb/> not insist on the uncompromising fidelity required of us, are<lb/> certain\n                of being popular and influential. My “<sic>dilenda</sic> est<lb/> Carthago” is the\n                onslaught in and out of the Pulpit on the<lb/> modern manufacture of a “Religion of\n                Convenience.” I have<lb/> confidence in the innate piety and good sense of the\n                people<lb/> who often, tho offenders against the the Law, do not palliate<lb/> or\n                argue away the wrong, and may be wrought on for their</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3542k15k/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
