              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3542k15k/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>might meet our wants;- a College — preparatory Schools — a<lb/> supervising Board to\n                examine into the qualifications &amp; personal<lb/> worth of those coming to this\n                country for office&amp;c? But no: it<lb/> seemed that the assembly of Delegates from\n                various parts of the<lb/> Union looked only to the aggrandizement of <placeName>New\n                    York</placeName>, and we<lb/> Dummies had only to listen with rapt attention to\n                the to the Delphic<lb/> oracles &amp; play the meek parts of “make weights.” I\n                hope<lb/> better things are in progress for I notice at last, some wakefullness<lb/>\n                on the great needs of one day. But perhaps my expectations<lb/> are premature, and\n                another <persName>Rip Van Winkle</persName> nap will follow.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Your article in the <date>June</date> No. is sound &amp;<lb/>\n                telling, and I trust to see it followed up by some tangible plan<lb/> for training\n                up an American ministry. It is singular that<lb/> our wealthy Congrns. have not been\n                influenced even by common<lb/> policy to do something even of a selfish nature for\n                their own<lb/> future advantage; and I throw out the hint which you might<lb/> use,\n                that lacking any general or organized effort, that each<lb/> might devote a portion\n                of its funds annually set apart to edu<lb/>cate in <placeName>Europe</placeName> —\n                after the usual Collegiate Course here — a<lb/> respectable &amp; pious-minded young\n                man, in whose services it<lb/> would have the first claim. My little boy I\n                    <sic>purpose</sic>, God<lb/> willing, bringing up to the sacred profession, and\n                if nothing better, or<lb/> as good offer here at the proper age to send him to\n                    <placeName>Breslau</placeName>; and<lb/> all my strivings peculiarly are devoted\n                towards this attainment,</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3542k15k/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
